description:
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Microbiology Biomedical Support Worker (Agenda for Change Band 3) (Fixed term contract: 1 year)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;We are delighted to be able to recruit to 3 Biomedical Support Workers to work within the Microbiology department of the Royal Devon and Exeter NHS Foundation Trust.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The Microbiology Department at the Royal Devon and Exeter NHS Foundation Trust is part of the Pathology service providing a diagnostic Microbiology service to the Trust and community. This forward thinking hospital is situated on the edge of Dartmoor in the city of Exeter with easy access to the M5 corridor and excellent transport links to the open countryside and Devon coastline. There is an on-site restaurant, crèche facilities and a choice of coffee/tea outlets. The laboratory has its own rest area within the department.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;An exciting opportunity has arisen to join our covid-19 testing team. As part of the team you will be working in a busy high throughput environment&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Your role will be to provide a 24/7 covid-19 testing service in both our Near Patient Testing Laboratory based in ED and the Microbiology department using rapid molecular detection platforms. You will receive full training to use and maintain automated equipment in the department to perform COVID assays.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;You must be keen to embrace new ways of working and develop your knowledge and skills in order to fulfil the role. You will be working with the Molecular senior team to ensure a co-ordinated and effective service is provided by best use of staff and resources to continue to provide a service to UKAS ISO 15189 standards. We are looking for an energetic, enthusiastic and well-motivated candidate with appropriate qualifications and/or relevant experience including laboratory skills for the accurate and safe use of laboratory equipment and reagents. To be the successful the candidate, as well as being friendly and reliable, you will need a flexible attitude towards work with good organisational skills, attention to detail and communication. You must have the ability to work under pressure and work well within a team.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Experience of laboratory work in a Pathology department would be an advantage, however all appropriate training will be given to the successful candidate.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Three posts are available working 37.5 hours per week. The department will be operating three shifts: Early 07:00am - 3.30pm, Late 15:00pm – 11.30pm and Nights 11:00 – 7:30.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Working on Saturdays, Sundays and Bank Holidays, on a rotational basis, is also required for this post.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Salary: Agenda for Change Band 3 (£19,737 - £21,142 pro rata).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Please note this vacancy will close as soon as sufficient applications have been received.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;For more information please contact Emma Hallett, Microbiology Services Manager, on 01392 402974.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;(This is a fixed term contract for 12 months.  For current NHS Employees this post could be a secondment opportunity)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Our vision is to provide safe, high quality seamless services delivered with courtesy and respect. To achieve our vision we expect all our staff to uphold our Trust values. Our Trust values are: &lt;br /&gt; Honesty, Openness &amp; Integrity&lt;br /&gt; Fairness&lt;br /&gt; Inclusion &amp; Collaboration&lt;br /&gt; Respect &amp; Dignity&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;***Preference will be given to staff with ‘Priority’ and &#39;At Risk&#39; status including NHS At Risk staff throughout Devon.***&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;DUE TO THE ANTICIPATED HIGH NUMBER OF APPLICATIONS FOR THIS POST WE RESERVE THE RIGHT TO CLOSE THE VACANCY BEFORE THE CLOSING DATE.&lt;/p&gt;
